SIMPLE: lighten
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lighten
<hw>Light"en</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"'n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Light</er> to alight.]</ety> <def>To descend; to light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O Lord, let thy mercy <qex>lighten</qex> upon us.</q>
<rj><qau>Book of Common Prayer [Eng. Ed.].</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lighten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lighten
<hw>Light"en</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"'n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lightened</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"'nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lightening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>lightenen</ets>. See
<er>Light</er> to kindle, illuminate.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To burst
forth or dart, as lightning; to shine with, or like, lightning; to
display a flash or flashes of lightning; to flash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This dreadful night,⟦br⟧
That thunders, <qex>lightens</qex>, opens graves, and roars⟦br⟧
As doth the lion.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To grow lighter; to become less dark or lowering; to
brighten; to clear, as the sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lighten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lighten
<hw>Light"en</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Light</er> to
illuminate.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make light or clear; to light; to
illuminate; <as>as, to <ex>lighten</ex> an apartment with lamps or gas;
to <ex>lighten</ex> the streets.</as></def> <mark>[In this sense less
common than <xex>light.</xex>]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A key of fire ran all along the shore,⟦br⟧
And <qex>lightened</qex> all the river with a blaze.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To illuminate with knowledge; to enlighten.</def>
<mark>[In this sense less common than <xex>enlighten</xex>.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Lighten</qex> my spirit with one clear heavenly ray.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To emit or disclose in, or as in, lightning; to
flash out, like lightning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His eye . . . <qex>lightens</qex> forth⟦br⟧
Controlling majesty.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To free from trouble and fill with joy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They looked unto him, and were <qex>lightened</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xxxiv. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lighten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lighten
<hw>Light"en</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Light</er> not
heavy.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make lighter, or less heavy; to reduce
in weight; to relieve of part of a load or burden; <as>as, to
<ex>lighten</ex> a ship by unloading; to <ex>lighten</ex> a load or
burden.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make less burdensome or afflictive; to alleviate;
<as>as, to <ex>lighten</ex> the cares of life or the burden of
grief</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cheer; to exhilarate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Lightens</qex> my humor with his merry jests.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>lightening</ent>⟦br⟧
